# Let's take a look at this graphically
dat <-
  db %>% 
  rename(cite = short_cite,
         yi = g_calc,
         vi = g_var_calc) %>% 
  mutate(study_ref = paste(cite, expt_num, same_infant, sep=',')) %>% 
  filter(gender >.01) %>% 
  arrange(desc(gender))
dat$se = sqrt(dat$vi)
dat$lowerci = (-1.96*dat$se)+dat$yi
dat$upperci = (1.96*dat$se)+dat$yi

ggplot(dat, aes(y=reorder(study_ref, -gender), x=yi, xmin=lowerci, xmax=upperci))+
  geom_point(aes(color = gender))+
  geom_errorbarh(height=.1)+
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(-1.5,1.5), name='Standardized Mean Difference (g)')+
  ylab('Reference')+
  geom_vline(xintercept=0, color='grey', linetype='dashed')+
  geom_vline(xintercept=0.65, color='black', linetype='dashed')

Future ideas

  • Id like to explore the studies demonstrating a familiarity preference. Are they a unique class? Or is it predictable random variation around the mean? Given the outliers in our funnel plots and the extreme degree of heterogeneity, I wonder if there are multiple things going on (rather, I think there are multiple things going on, can we figure out what they are?)
